<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="684" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,906,1329]" pageId="6" pageNumber="684">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,978,1004]" pageId="6" pageNumber="684">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Recognized and differing from congeners by the largest and most conspicuous triangular median thoracic ridge widening posteriorly, where it is three times as wide as at the level of pronotum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="684" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,906,1329]" pageId="6" pageNumber="684">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1050,1076]" pageId="6" pageNumber="684">Description.</emphasis>
This new species shares all essential characters as given in the generic description, which are not necessarily repeated here. It is the smallest of the three species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,906,1329]" pageId="6" pageNumber="684">
<emphasis box="[199,369,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="684">Measurements.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[377,486,1123,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="684">Holotype</typeStatus>
: Length 3.40; head length / width 0.75 / 0.75; pronotum length / width 0.35 / 1.05; mesonotum with 1.25; metanotum width 1.50; ratio length of antennae / width of head 2.33; length of antennal segments I / II / III / IV, 0.75 / 0.30 / 0.35 / 0.35; width of abdomen across tergites III-VII 1.50 / 1.50 / 1.60 / 1.80 / 1.10.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1427,1267,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="684" type="etymology">
